{"key":"post-12671193","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12671193</id>\n<content>First of all, perlite doesn't create too much humidity.&amp;nbsp; In fact, there's no such thing as too much humidity.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms fruit in the fog after rains in 100%.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;You can't re-case.&amp;nbsp; The mold was in your spawn and only sporulated on the surface.&amp;nbsp; Toss it out.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd suggest building a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;shotgun terrarium&lt;/a&gt;, or a larger humidity tent, but put lots of holes in it for fresh air.&amp;nbsp; Stale air stimulates molds, fresh air stimulates mushroom mycelium.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Any holes you make are not CO2 vents.&amp;nbsp; They're air vents.&amp;nbsp; Any CO2 produced by the substrate mixes with the air, and both need to be vented and replaced.&amp;nbsp; It's a common mistake by new growers to think CO2 will 'drain' out holes in the bottom, but this isn't the case.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12671205</next>\n<prev>12671101</prev>\n<first>12671101</first>\n<last>12671205</last>\n<when>1275489192</when>\n<utime>06/02/10 05:33 PM</utime>\n</post>"}